    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-08-22T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-08-22T17:00:00-05:00" n="59"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d59">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5151/497: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the First
                        Secretary of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Salisbury</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">at Peiping</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-08-22T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 22, 1938—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>222. Please repeat the following telegram to Chefoo and ask Chefoo to repeat to
                    you its telegram of August 12, 1 p.m., to the Department.<note n="61"
                        xml:id="d59fn61">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“Reference your telegrams of June 13, 10 a.m., and August 12, 1 p.m., and
                        despatch No. 10 of June 24<note n="62" xml:id="d59fn62">None printed.</note>
                        in regard to the currency situation in the Chefoo consular district.</p>
                    <pb facs="0045" n="41" xml:id="pg_41"/>
                    <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>As ‘Federal Reserve notes’ are not the lawful currency of the
                            recognized Government of China, every endeavor should be made to avoid
                            any official action which might be construed as promoting the
                            circulation of these notes.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Department of course realizes that circumstances may require the
                            Consulate and the American business community at Chefoo to use ‘Federal
                            Reserve notes’ in meeting necessary local expenses.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Please report by telegraph on the following matters: When and for what
                            reason did the Yokohama Specie Bank in Chefoo cease foreign exchange
                            operations? Is there no agency whatever in Chefoo willing to accept
                            American currency in exchange for ‘Federal Reserve notes’? Is it not
                            possible for American merchants in Chefoo to evolve some method of
                            meeting their currency requirements as for example by negotiating at
                            Tientsin for exchange of American currency for valid Chinese currency or
                            ‘Federal Reserve notes’?”</item>
                    </list>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
